# Review of `app.js`

The current file is minimal (23 lines), so most of these are improvements you'd want before this gets any larger. Below is a prioritized list with concrete code.

## Issues found

### 1. No security headers
Every response is missing baseline protections (X-Frame-Options, CSP, HSTS, etc.). Add `helmet`.

### 2. No rate limiting
Both routes are wide open — trivial to DoS or scrape.

### 3. No error-handling middleware
An uncaught error in a future handler will crash the process or leak stack traces. Express needs an explicit `(err, req, res, next)` handler.

### 4. No `app.listen` error handler
If port 3000 is taken or binding fails, the error is unhandled.

### 5. No process-level handlers
`unhandledRejection` / `uncaughtException` will silently crash Node.

### 6. Hardcoded port + no graceful shutdown
Should come from `process.env.PORT`, and SIGTERM/SIGINT should close the server cleanly.

### 7. No body parser limits (for future POST routes)
Once you add `express.json()`, set a `limit` to prevent memory-exhaustion attacks.

### 8. No input validation scaffolding
`/users` doesn't accept input yet, but there's no pattern in place. When you add `/users/:id` or query params, you'll need validation (e.g., `zod` or `express-validator`).

### 9. `timestamp` in `/health` is fine, but `/health` leaks info
In production, consider a separate `/health` (liveness, minimal) and `/ready` (readiness). Don't include build info unless gated.

### 10. Trust proxy not set
If deployed behind a load balancer, `req.ip` will be wrong and rate-limiters will treat all traffic as one client.

---

## Suggested rewrite

```js
const express = require('express');
const helmet = require('helmet');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const app = express();

// --- Security middleware ---
app.set('trust proxy', 1); // if behind a proxy/LB
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 60 * 1000,
  max: 100,
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
});
app.use(limiter);

// --- Routes ---
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'ok', timestamp: new Date().toISOString() });
});

app.get('/users', (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    const users = [
      { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
      { id: 2, name: 'Bob', email: 'bob@example.com' },
    ];
    res.json(users);
  } catch (err) {
    next(err);
  }
});

// --- 404 ---
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });
});

// --- Error handler (must have 4 args) ---
app.use((err, req, res, _next) => {
  // Log full error server-side, never to the client
  console.error(err);
  const status = err.status || 500;
  res.status(status).json({
    error: status >= 500 ? 'Internal server error' : err.message,
  });
});

// --- Server lifecycle ---
const PORT = Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000;
const server = app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});

server.on('error', (err) => {
  console.error('Server failed to start:', err);
  process.exit(1);
});

const shutdown = (signal) => {
  console.log(`${signal} received, shutting down`);
  server.close(() => process.exit(0));
  setTimeout(() => process.exit(1), 10_000).unref();
